@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Putting It All Together";
}

<div class="container">
    <h1>Putting It All Together</h1>

    <div class="alert alert-success">
        <i class="fas fa-flag-checkered"></i>
        <strong>This is it.</strong> Everything you’ve learned so far leads to this point.
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
        Up until now, you have been learning individual pieces:
        projects, MVC, Identity, models, and databases.
        On the next page, you will see how <strong>all of that connects into one real application</strong>.
    </p>

    <hr class="my-4" />

    <div class="section-card">
        <h2>What You Already Know</h2>
        <ul class="checklist">
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle text-success"></i> How to create an ASP.NET MVC project</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle text-success"></i> What Models, Views, and Controllers are</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle text-success"></i> How Entity Framework works</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle text-success"></i> What ASP.NET Identity is</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle text-success"></i> How databases and migrations work</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section-card">
        <h2>What You Are About To Build</h2>
        <p>
            On the next page, you will build a <strong>real-world scenario</strong>:
        </p>

        <ul class="checklist">
            <li><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> An MVC application with <strong>Individual User Accounts</strong></li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> A <strong>custom Identity user</strong></li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> A <strong>Student → Courses</strong> relationship</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Automatic CRUD generation</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr class="my-4" />

    <div class="section-card highlight-card">
        <h2>What You Should Do</h2>
        <ol class="step-list">
            <li>
                <strong>Read each step carefully</strong><br />
                Don’t rush. This is about understanding, not speed.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Try to write the code yourself first</strong><br />
                Even if it’s wrong — that’s how learning happens.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>If you get stuck — don’t panic</strong><br />
                The next page contains <em>click-to-reveal solutions</em> for every step.
            </li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-info mt-4">
        <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i>
        <strong>Important:</strong> Getting stuck is expected.
        Professional developers get stuck every day — the difference is knowing
        <em>how to continue</em>.
    </div>

    <hr class="my-4" />

    <div class="final-note">
        <h2>You Are Ready</h2>
        <p>
            If you understand even <strong>60–70%</strong> of what’s coming next,
            you are already ahead of most beginners.
        </p>
        <p>
            Go to the next page, follow the steps, and remember:
            <strong>everything is revealed if you need help</strong>.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("Summary", "Web")" class="btn btn-outline-secondary ajax-link">
            <i class="fas fa-home"></i> Previous chapter
        </a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("BuldingSteps", "WebApp")" class="btn btn-primary ajax-link">
            Start the Full Tutorial <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
        </a>
    </div>
</div>

